    "summary": "After leaving school I first studied to become an English-Dutch interpreter/translator (graduated 1973), and in 1984 I received my teacher's degree (MO-A) in English. In 1985 I went to the University of Amsterdam to study General Linguistics (MA in 1989). I got my PhD in 2000, while already working at the Hogeschool Utrecht, setting up the bachelor programme for Teacher/Interpreter NGT (Sign Language of the Netherlands) and in 2004 a master programme in Deaf Studies. In September 2007 I was appointed Professor (Lector) of Deaf Studies at the Faculty of Education at the HU. From 2013-2019 I was Professor of NGT at the University of Amsterdam, which is still my affiliation as emeritus professor. \n\nThrough my research and teaching I gained a lot of knowledge about disabilities, human (linguistic) rights and on curriculum development and teaching/pedagogy. I am an advocate for changes in our Dutch educational system - it really is time to a) pump a substantial amount of money in primary, secondary and tertiary education (Life Long Learning) and b) let go of all the testing and strict rules, and adapt our system to what we now know about how people learn. Not sitting down in classrooms and learning for tests! \n\nSince 2019, I am a guest lecturer in the master program Deafblindness at University Groningen.\n\nSince 2019 I am a member of Volt Nederland and Volt Europe, where I was in the Editing team (NL) and co-lead of the Editorial Team for the new Volt EUR Manifesto. Now Volt Duo-member in the Provincial State of North-Holland. This means I get to sit in commission, but cannot vote. We have two Volt representatives  (Julia Schneemann and Maik de Weerdt) and two duo-members (me and Bart Bonekamp). We are ready to go!",
